John Edward: Key Linguistic Skills for Global Citizens
Private schools in Scotland hold the record for academic excellence and this has continued in 2018 with another succession of excellent exam results, further reinforced by individual and collective success in sports, arts, music and other fields.
With over 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Private Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the highest level of service to their students and parents.
Private schools aim to prepare their students for further education at the highest levels, for the career of their choice and their place as global citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a tailored educational curriculum, we are witnessing how modern language learning continues to be a widespread and popular choice across schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, "If you speak to someone in a language that they understand, your words come to their ears.
If you speak to him in your own language, your words go to his heart.”
These words are a powerful reminder that we can't rely only on English when we want to build relationships with people from foreign countries.
From the results of this year's latest exams, we can find that languages are leading the lists of results, with the highest rate of passing grades among private schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who have studied a foreign language have received a maximum A rating.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students had received a maximum A score in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who studied German, 69 percent of those who studied A scores for French and 63 percent of those who studied German.
This shows that private schools in Scotland are supporting foreign languages as one of the vital skills that will definitely be needed by children and young people in the future.
Currently, foreign language skills are considered as important as STEM branches (science, technology, engineering, and mathematics) in the curricula of private schools and beyond.
A 2014 study by the United Kingdom Commission on Employment and Skills found that among the main difficulties employers faced in filling vacancies, 17 percent of them were related to a lack of language skills.
As a result, language skills are becoming more and more necessary for preparing young people for their upcoming careers.
With the increase in jobs that have as a condition of foreign language proficiency, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career a person chooses, if he has learned a second language, he will have real advantages in the future, as the master of such a long-term ability.
The ability to communicate directly with foreign people will automatically position a multilingual person over the competition.
According to a survey by YouGov, which included over 4,000 adults from the UK in 2013, 75 percent of them were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation, and French was the only one-to-one language spoken by 15 people.
That's why investing in language learning is so important for today's children.
The mastery of many languages, in particular the mastery of the languages of developing countries, will give children a better chance of employment.
Within Scotland, each school will be different in terms of the languages taught in them.
Some schools will focus on the most classical modern languages, while others will offer languages that are considered to be most important for the UK in the 2020 perspective, such as the Mandarin or Japanese language.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be a variety of languages from which you can choose in private schools, with pedagogical staff composed of specialists in the field.
Scottish private schools are dedicated to providing a school environment that will prepare children and "armate" them with the skills they need to cope with, no matter what the future holds.
In these times it cannot be denied that in a global business environment, languages continue to have a vital importance for the future of the country, so this should be reflected in education.
Modern languages should really be considered as "the skill of international communication".
Private schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity, and excellence to the youth of Scotland.
We have to do it right.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Board of Private Schools.
