The creator of the World Wide Web plans to launch a new internet to compete with Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, founder of the World Wide Web, is creating a company that aims to rival Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of the technology legend, ‘Inrupt’, is a company built by Berners-Lee’s open-source platform, called ‘Solid’.
‘Solid’ allows users to choose where their data is stored and which persons are allowed to have access to certain information.
In an exclusive interview with 'Fast Company', Berners-Lee joked that the goal after 'Inrupt' is 'world dominance'.
"We have to do it now," he said of this innovative company.
"It's a historic moment."
The app uses Solid's technology to allow people to create "the creation of their personal data on the network" or a POD.
It can include contact lists, lists of things to do, music lists, and other personal and professional tools.
It's the same as having it available in a browser and at the same time Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify.
What is unique about the storage of personal data on the network is the fact that it remains entirely at the user's disposal as to what kind of information they will access.
The company calls this "personal empowerment through data."
The idea for Inrupt, according to the company's CEO, John Bruce, is to bring together the right resources, processes, and capabilities to help Solid be available to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased from IBM, several developers contracted to work on this project, and a community of volunteer coders.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world can create their decentralized applications using the tools available on the Inrupt's website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team are not talking to "Facebook and Google whether or not they should present a total change where all of their business models are flooded completely overnight.
"We're not asking for their permission."
In a post in 'Medium' published Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that Inrupt's mission "is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem that helps protect the integrity and quality of the new network built in Solid."
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
Over the past few months, Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in the debate over network bias.
Even as he founded Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the consortium of the World Wide Web, the Network Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
"I'm very optimistic about this new era of networking," Berners-Lee added.
